{"type":"step-attempt","step":"cross-boundary-invariants","sessionId":"58a42315-d056-4760-b892-3c35b0a2cc8e","outcome":{"verdict":"approved","findingsPath":"specrunner/changes/request-review-factcheck-attestation/cross-boundary-invariants-result-001.md","error":null,"toolResult":{"ok":true,"approved":true,"findings":[{"severity":"low","resolution":"fixable","file":"src/core/step/design.ts","title":"Attestation consumption not declared in DesignStep.reads() — asymmetric io-contract","rationale":"The attestation file (factCheckAttestationPath) is declared as a write in RequestReviewStep.writes() with verify:false, but is NOT declared as a read in DesignStep.reads(). The formal io-contracts system (validateRequiredInputs) is unaware of this cross-step dependency. A future enforcement of 'all enrichContext reads must be declared in reads()' would require a retrofit. Non-blocking because absence degrades fail-safely (absent → verify all), and adding it as required:false read provides no additional runtime protection given current degradation behavior."},{"severity":"low","resolution":"fixable","file":"src/prompts/request-review-system.ts","title":"codeAssertionsVerified:true is a process flag (Step 2 ran), not a correctness flag (Step 2 passed)","rationale":"The attestation spec declares codeAssertionsVerified always true when the attestation is written, even if Step 2 recorded HIGH findings (assertion mismatches). The invariant that design only processes a valid attestation post-approve is enforced by the pipeline state machine, not by the data contract. If the state machine invariant is bypassed, design could skip assertions with known mismatches. Acknowledged trade-off in design.md Risks section; mitigation is pipeline sequencing (design only reachable after approve verdict). No runtime impact under normal operation."}],"observations":[{"severity":"low","file":"src/core/step/design.ts","title":"Temporal coupling between request-review commit and design enrichContext not expressed in contracts","rationale":"DesignStep.enrichContext reads the attestation from the local worktree after request-review has committed it. This sequential dependency is guaranteed by the pipeline's step-by-step execution model but is not encoded in any formal contract. In the managed runtime, enrichContext read failures degrade gracefully (absent → verify all). No correctness risk under the current architecture."}]},"followUpAttempts":1,"transientRetryAttempts":0},"startedAt":"2026-07-14T08:54:09.860Z","endedAt":"2026-07-14T09:00:44.391Z"}
